<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-chi_square-Distribution" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>The <m>\chi^2</m> Distribution</title>
  <p>
    The <m>\chi^2</m> (Chi-square) distribution is another important continuous probability distribution. 
    Unlike the Normal and <m>t</m> distributions, it is defined only for positive values and is usually 
    positively skewed. The amount of skewness depends on the degrees of freedom. As the degrees of freedom 
    increase, the distribution becomes more symmetrical.
  </p>
  <p>
    The Chi-square distribution is widely used in statistical methods involving categorical data and measures 
    of variability. Later in this book it will be used in Chi-square tests of independence and goodness-of-fit.
  </p>
  <p>
    Select the <em>Chi-square</em> distribution in the <em>Show Model</em> dialog and experiment with different 
    values for the degrees of freedom. Observe how the distribution changes from being strongly skewed for small 
    degrees of freedom to becoming more symmetric as the degrees of freedom increase.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig-chisqdist">
    <caption>
        Chi-square distributions with three degrees of freedom. Notice that the distribution begins at zero 
        and is positively skewed.
    </caption>
    <image source="images/chisqdist.png"/>
  </figure>
</subsection>